<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870821-0048 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief:Ingersoll-Rand Co.</HL><DD> 08/21/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> IR </IN><TEXT>   Nippon Seiko K.K. and Ingersoll-Rand Co.'s Torrington Co. unit said they agreed in principle to make automotive steering-column systems in North America.    Torrington and Nippon Seiko currently have a joint venture in Japan that makes needle roller bearings for Japanese auto makers. Ingersoll-Rand, which makes machinery and bearings, is based in Woodcliff Lake, N.J. Nippon Seiko, of Japan, makes bearings and parts for autos and machinery.    A spokesman for Torrington said a location for the new venture hasn't been established, but the company expects to complete the accord in the fourth quarter. He declined to disclose financial terms. </TEXT></DOC>